one day, quietly, with no warning, she said, "will you hold me?"
and so he did, of course. his arms around her in an embrace that fitted his body to hers. kissing her hair, eyelids, tip of nose. asking, "did something go wrong? did you have a scare?"
she seems not to have heard, her arms around him tight, tight.
feeling against her cheek the comforting scratchiness of the wool sweater she'd knitted him years ago. when they were newly lovers.
minutes passed. how very odd. he felt her trembling -- a deep subterranean shuttering. he asked,
"you didn't have an accident with your car, did you?" and,
"did someone threaten you?" and, "what is it?"
still she made no reply. gripping him close.
so he was having difficulty breathing. so his heartbeat quickened, as if in the presence of danger.
he said, "darling, please, i love you - what is it?"
he tried gently to push her away from him, just a bit, so that he could see her face. for, suddenly, it seemed to him he could not recall her face.
but she was holding him tight, tight.
saying, almost inaudibly, so that he felt rather than heard her words, "just hold me."
"yes, but -- what is it?"
how many minutes of this embrace could he endure? five? ten? sixty? one thousand? he said, bravely, "yes. i'm here."
outside, an unexpected rain pelted against the windows -- or was that sunshine? that sudden glare?

20 snippets about me, in no particular order:
1) i am dutch-indonesian. i was born in holland, raised in amsterdam.
2) my native tongue & passport are both dutch.
3) i don't think i will ever give up my passport, even though the dutch don't allow dual citizenship.
4) i moved to california before i turned 18, which is why i have never voted in my life.
5) my mother and i moved to the us to start a new life, away from my father. my father is a bad man, and by that i don't mean bad-ass. we chose the bay area, because we picked a place on the map where neither one of us had been to before.
6) my mother moved back to holland 10 years ago. i have no blood-relatives here, and sometimes this really freaks me out.
7) i went to 5 high schools, in 2 countries, over a period of 2 years & graduated in 3 years at the age of 16.
8) i moved out when i was 16 to live with my boyfriend who was 9 years older. 3 1/2 years later, at the age of 19, i moved back home not knowing what it was like to be single.
9) i have a 17 year younger brother. 17 years is exactly one generation. i want to get to know him.
10) my hair has been purple for 12 years.
for most of my life i had very long, dark, thick hair. one day i tried to imagine myself without hair, and i couldn't: the thought of having it all gone was so frightening, i had no other option but to shave it all off. when my hair grew back out, i dyed it purple, and it's been purple ever since.
11) i rode horses competitively for most of my life: showjumping.
i had the most incredible grey thoroughbred gelding: woody. short for kirkwood [the mountain]. i won the junior grand national in 1990, and i actually went pro for one year. once in college, i started to read too much philosophy & i couldn't bear to put a bit in my horse's mouth any longer; i couldn't put a saddle on him anymore. i retired him & haven't ridden since then.
12) i raced cars for one year: a 1982 black 911 porsche carrera, 3.5 liter engine. whale tail. license plate: cujo35
13) i rode a motorcycle for 6 years. it was my only source of transportation during that time. and there was never a day that went by without a close call. i miss my bike a lot, though & still have plans to get another one.
14) i worked as a dom during my junior year in college. what began as a purely anthropological and intellectual endeavor really turned out to be a deeply emotional can of worms. the day this became clear, i quit. i know that endeavors #12, 13 and 14 were integral to my growth during those years. and by integral i mean that these things were a combination of symptom, catharsis, self-discovery, healing and, in retrospect, they are each very metaphorical. so don't get too excited about this one ;-)
15) i graduated with a 3.95 from berkeley, where i double-majored in english and dutch literature.
16) i worked as a teaching assistant for two years afterwards--i probably graded over 2000 papers during that time.
17) i received a full scholarship to pursue a phd in literature at berkeley, but dropped out after 4 semesters. my decision to leave academia was one of the toughest choices i have ever had to make. i am glad i made that decision, though, as i feel that academia was too good of a hiding place for me (see #20).
18) it took me 28 years to discover the banana. i hated bananas for the first 28 years of my life.
19) i have three tattoos. the first is on my back: a phoenix. the second on my stomach: a lotus. the third on my right arm: a muted posthorn. the muted posthorn comes from my favorite novel, the crying of lot 49 by thomas pynchon.
20) it took me 34 years to discover that i am a serious work-a-holic. i'm slowly coming to terms with this.

it doesn't interest me
what you do for a living.
i want to know
what you ache for
and if you dare to dream
of meeting your heart's longing.

it doesn't interest me
how old you are.
i want to know
if you will risk
looking like a fool
for love
for your dream
for the adventure of being alive.

it doesn't interest me
what planets are
squaring your moon...
i want to know
if you have touched
the centre of your own sorrow
if you have been opened
by life's betrayals
or have become shrivelled and closed
from fear of further pain.

i want to know
if you can sit with pain
mine or your own
without moving to hide it
or fade it
or fix it.

i want to know
if you can be with joy
mine or your own
if you can dance with wildness
and let the ecstasy fill you
to the tips of your fingers and toes
without cautioning us
to be careful
to be realistic
to remember the limitations
of being human.

it doesn't interest me
if the story you are telling me
is true.
i want to know if you can
disappoint another
to be true to yourself.
if you can bear
the accusation of betrayal
and not betray your own soul.
if you can be faithless
and therefore trustworthy.

i want to know if you can see beauty
even when it is not pretty
every day.
and if you can source your own life
from its presence.

i want to know
if you can live with failure
yours and mine
and still stand at the edge of the lake
and shout to the silver of the full moon,
yes.

it doesn't interest me
to know where you live
or how much money you have.
i want to know if you can get up
after the night of grief and despair
weary and bruised to the bone
and do what needs to be done
to feed the children.

it doesn't interest me
who you know
or how you came to be here.
i want to know if you will stand
in the centre of the fire
with me
and not shrink back.

it doesn't interest me
where or what or with whom
you have studied.
i want to know
what sustains you
from the inside
when all else falls away.

i want to know
if you can be alone
with yourself
and if you truly like
the company you keep
in the empty moments.

here is one story..

having finally decided that it was in my best interest to get back to the states, i said farewell to my friends and acquaintances in northern france. it had been a long 11 months of adventure and due to my procrastination to return, i had a mere 3 days until my fixed ticket return flight from amsterdam to san francisco.

as usual, i had no money. cedric, my traveling companion for much of that 11 months was sorry to see me go. he left me playing music on the streets in caen. i made the usual 30 francs and hopped on the train.... without a ticket.

the train from caen to paris was a pleasant evening ride. no pesky controller looking for tickets. paris of course was a different story. a few days prior, a bomb had gone off in the subway and the station was combing with military police. i chickened out on 3 of the 4 evening bullet trains headed to amsterdam. tickets were being checked prior to boarding which was not the usual drill. i sat around nervously for hours until i had no choice. the last train was boarding.

i watched all the normal passengers line up, until finally the telecom announced final boarding call. people now in a hurry. the controllers started blowing their whistles. military police, dogs and guns walking in their calculated patterns.

it was my chance. i ran towards the train, the engines were starting up. i was waving towards my imaginary parents when i was stopped and asked for my ticket. "ticket?" i said surprised. "oh right, shit! it's somewhere in my bag." i began to look through my backpack. "just get on!" he said, obviously annoyed, "we'll check it inside, the train is leaving".

inside, i was overwhelmed with relief. i kept going until i felt i was about in the center of the train. by the time i found a cabin, the train had been on the move for a good 10 minutes. i choose to sit next to a disheveled looking moroccan for strategic reasons, knowing that the prejudice of the french would take attention away from me. it's hard to actually evade the controllers on the bullet trains since there are few stops where you can get on and off. this evening was a simple matter of getting as far north as possible.

i took a nap.

i was woken up to the sight and sound of 2 meaty looking controllers making fun of the moroccan guys passport (i have to admit it was in bad shape). my french isn't very good, but i believe they where debating whether or not it was counterfeit. they finally decided it was valid and turned to me. "ticket and passport". i handed over my passport and told them that i was late to the station and that my family was on somewhere with my ticket. they were clearly not amused and talked to themselves. the bigger of the two, leaned towards me while the other one was writing down my passport information. "he showed me the price of the ticket on his calculator. "i suspect your family also has your money?". they radioed in. "there are no others corbin's on the train, come with us."

the conversation to the operating switch was in a phrase: matter of fact. the whistle began to blow. an announcement went over the speakers. the train would be making an unscheduled stop. the screeching of the wheels began. it took about 10 minutes for the train to finally come to a halt. by that time, i had been escorted to an exit point, a firm grip on my arm the entire time.

the doors slid open and i was literally pushed out.

outside, there was a beautiful midnight sky. in fact i had made it about 2 hours north of paris and looking around quickly got the impression that this was a quaint french ville, in the middle of nowhere. the controllers were laughing and yelling obscenities that made no sense. the train began to start. it's wheels straining under the gigantic weight to build up to it's bullet speeds.

i watched the momentum and noticed an interesting detail.

it wasn't just the door that i was thrown out of that had opened. all the doors had opened. i watched them pass me by. one by one, each moving slightly faster and i felt hypnotized in a way that only happens when you have made up your mind to do something crazy. with a brave (and admittedly clumsy) leap.

i was back in the train.

it was dark and i soon realized that i was in first class. everyone had their own cabins and i began making my way towards the back of the train, hoping to find a place where i could blend in. i finally made it as far as i could go. the door to second class was locked....

this is a burning man story - my last year was my seventh burn, and i went out to the basura sagrada on the night of the burn with a friend. i had had a really hard year - working through a divorce, an old burner lover died of an overdose, laid off from my job, a close artistic partner had died randomly out of the blue... and here i was at the temple reflecting on all that.
i had done a tarot reading for myself recently which is generally pretty accurate and the general reading was that i was going to manage and balance things very well. except up there, on the temple i didn't feel like it all. i didn't feel strong and adaptable. i felt alone and broken down. not sure about my future. just too much random shit happening throughout my life. so many dead friends too young, no security, love just not working out. not like i wanted to throw a pity party for myself, it was just all coming to head right there. and so i'm sitting on the upper level of the temple in ridiculously high winds and the whole structure is shaking and the pieces of junk that the construction team has nailed to the frame are all rattling and waving and suddenly it hits me.
i'm as strong as the temple. you can take pieces of junk, things that other people have thrown away and discarded, and turn them into something beautiful. the wind can blow as hard as it likes, but the structure isn't coming down. one because it's built right, but also because there are 50 thousand people out here right now who have put their belief, their spirit right into this thing. yes, it's formed from all these broken things, but ultimately it's the strongest platform on the playa. and i'm just as broken, flawed, and as strong as the temple.

and the wind stops.

one of my earliest memories - certainly the earliest that i can easily recall - is of being nearly 4 years old at the first house i lived in on park street in new iberia. i was sitting at the kitchen table to a dinner of grits and eggs. i know that grits and eggs is typically considered breakfast food, but i grew up in a household where breakfast wasn't just the most important meal of the day; it was my favorite. so i ate it at every meal.

i was pushing 4 and yearning for independence, so i wanted to eat all by myself, and with a fork. my dad was fine with that, but he had to stand over me while i ate - just to make sure that i didn't puncture my tonsils with the newly-weaponized eating utensil.

this happened around 1983 back when parents weren't so cautious about exposing their kids to second-hand smoke. my parents happened to be smokers and my dad stood over me while i ate my... brinner(?) with a cigarette dangling from his lips. then the unthinkable happened. a long chunk of cigarette ash fell from his cigarette and right into the center of my plate. as a child, i took food very seriously. when pleased with a meal i was known to hum and wiggle my toes. when displeased, i would do precisely what i did when my dad's disgusting cigarette ashes plopped into my meal: i wailed like a baby.

my dad didn't know what to do. three kids, 3.5 years of fatherhood, and never had he unintentionally inspired that much unhappiness. not knowing what else to do, and seeking to immediately alleviate the situation, he grabbed a fork, spooned up the heap of grits with the offending ashes, and ate it. "see? it's ok to eat!"

i'm not sure that i've cried harder since that moment.

now cigarette ashes really freak me out.

this beautiful rumi quote sums up my approach to relationship pretty well.

i believe if two people are able to communicate deeply, from a place of non-judgment and non-blame, they can almost always find empathy for each other. even if they disagree, it's possible, in my experience, to come to a deep understanding of each other that builds respect and connection over time.

my early relationships, including my long-ago marriage, were in what i consider a conventional relationship model -- we enjoyed the good and didn't effectively deal with the problems, irritants and judgments that inevitably cropped up. as long as the good exceeded the bad, we were okay. but by leaving the weeds untended, they eventually overtook the garden.

most relationships seem to work like this, with or without the divorce... which is why i'd rather be single than in most relationships i've seen....

i need a partner who is committed to actively nurturing the relationship. communicating about issues is not the dominant part of the relationship -- what would be the point? -- but tending the garden is a priority for me.

to create an emotionally transparent relationship, a compatible fellow would need to know his own emotional landscape and be committed to compassionately and non-judgmentally working through the baggage -- his, hers and ours.

if you believe you have no need to explore your psyche, no desire to do relationship processing and/or no experience doing either of the above, we are most likely incompatible.

but i do wish you the best! godspeed in finding your dream girl.

-----------------------------------
synchronicity is the experience of two or more events that are apparently causally unrelated or unlikely to occur together by chance, yet are experienced as occurring together in a meaningful manner. the concept of synchronicity was first described in this terminology by carl gustav jung, a swiss psychologist, in the 1920s.[1]

the concept does not question, or compete with, the notion of causality. instead it maintains that, just as events may be grouped by cause, they may also be grouped by meaning. a grouping of events by meaning need not have an explanation in terms of cause and effect.

i really want to be in that place with someone. that conversational place; the place where strange conversations about random things flow freely and inside jokes form. the place where you learn more about yourself through talking about everything imaginable and learn just as much about another person. to me the greatest feeling is knowing someone and having them know you in return. really knowing, not just a casual understanding. i can have great conversations with strangers and people i don't know very well (that brings a different kind of satisfaction, which has its place too), but it isn't nearly as satisfying as feeling completely understood by someone and becoming close as a result. for me, this is a relationship. sure; sex is there, attraction is there, common interest is there, but the most intricate, yet simple, aspect of a relationship is the conversation that comes with it. the conversation that happens while laying with your heads upside-down and dangling off the edge of the bed, the conversation that happens when you're half-asleep and hardly making sense, the conversation that goes on at 3 am - when all the best ideas surface, the conversation that happens in every setting, and the conversation that isn't conversation at all, but silence. to be able to sit comfortably with someone without the need to talk -when "awkward" silences are just silences. a lot is said in nothing - when sounds become decipherable words that mean something to you, while nothing to others. but i'm not in that place right now - that conversational place - where everything is beautiful and meaningful.

when i was in my 20s, i used to be really into dating guys who wanted to have competitions about who is hipper. let's argue about books, music, art woo! i wanted to hang out with self-identified writers and artists and musicians, as if we were all lounging in a salon in paris or the factory in new york.

now, that just makes me tired. i could care less if you're cool. it is important, for the sake of feeling understood, that the man i date has what i call "poet's eyes," something like amelie's view of the world. he can be delighted by the feeling of sticking his hand in a barrel grains, or will describe to me the overwhelming hue of the blue flowers he saw on a hike.

i want to date a man who assumes he likes people, who can look at someone who is very different than he is, and see the common thread of humanity, something to empathize and connect with. i have a bit of a dark, cynical streak, but i am honestly over snark, even inside myself. i am not over ranting about politics, though.

what's most important to me, at this stage in my life, is finding a partner. i do want a serious boyfriend, and i would like to get married. i have to figure out pretty quickly whether i want to make babies, and i don't like it, but that's the biological truth. what i'm looking for in a husband/life partner/potential baby daddy is someone who will share with cooking and chores equally, and create a space where we offer each other mutual support as well as fun, romance, and adventure.

i'm not entirely convinced this is the place to find that sort of partner. my heart is still healing from the last time i fell in love, and i've been through a tremendous amount of upheaval in the past two years. right now, i need to spend time alone, or with my friends, to put my life back together and make sure i'm building the kind of life i want to have. that's where i'm at.

that said, i'll go out of my mind if i spend the next six month to a year all work, no play. so let's play.

have you ever noticed how "private" is relative? some people will tell you the number of people they've slept with but balk at the number on their paychecks. others feel exactly the opposite. that said, in the interest of fulfilling the purpose of this poorly-worded question, story time:

once i kissed someone whose name i don't remember, just because he asked me nicely. i hadn't told him my correct name, and i ended up checking the oil in my pickup myself (which was what i told him he had to do for the kiss), but i kissed him anyway. i still remember the cool softness of his lips and the lingering sweet-spicy taste of his clove cigarette. he tried to talk me out of reapplying my lipstick quite so soon, but when i did it anyway he held his peace.

i like that in a person. i generally respond well to people who are willing to ask for what they want, plainly but with no expectations, and then accept when i give all i'm willing to up front and draw the line. push and push back is good, and persistence is a virtue, but there is a definite limit to that when boundaries have been clearly defined.

and...
there is a candle in my window for someone i've never met, but the person who can answer it is a very rare sort, and may not even exist. i'm comfortable with this. someday, it would be nice to find a real partner, one who understands me and unconsciously speaks the same language of love, who loves the way sharing enriches the lives of all involved but will give me priority, whom i can engage with in the dance of love and life, who will support and uplift and work with me as much as i do for them, with as little complaint. someone who understands the need to love deeply, and hold each other lightly.
only once has anyone ever loved me enough to give me up and help me go my way, and to get me to commit to a partnership, i'd need another love that strong. i'm not sure i believe i'm blessed enough to experience such a precious and rare thing more than once in one lifetime.

i grabbed onto our side of the line and he stepped off the deck. and fell straight to the ground. the pulley on the other end had come out of the tree it'd been anchored to, and my stubby 12 year old fingers hadn't been able to hold onto our end, either.

most of my friends have advised me to leave this fact about myself out of my profile on the grounds that it's not necessary to be so forthcoming before you really know someone, and that people might have their own prejudices against alcoholics (recovered or not). i used to agree. however, i've recently changed changed the way i feel about this. on one hand, i think it is important enough to disclose to anyone who who would consider going out with me, since the question about drinks and why i don't drink would probably surface early on anyway. i don't want to waste anyone's time, or mine.

the way i feel now is that the person i wish to attract is someone for which this wouldn't be such a big deal and who would rather respect someone who's faced adversity and turned their life around. so we'll see what happens. if one year passes by without any responses on this site, perhaps i'll consider deleting this. ;)

once, many years ago, i was on a road trip in tibet. our first stop was ganden monastery, a place on top of a very big hill. there were a whole bunch of statues, lots of yak butter candles, and i had a mala blessed for my friend. after the tour, i asked my guide if i could go up behind the monastery and look out onto the valley below. "sure!" he said. i scrambled up the rocky slope, and cast my gaze across the himalayas. there was a tibetan family picnicking on the other side of the mountain. the mother was peeing right there in the open, probably because she had too much coffee that morning.

after a few minutes of that splendid vista, i decided to not keep the driver waiting. i felt my way back down the hill, but couldn't quite find the same path. all of a sudden, a dog came out of nowhere and started barking at me!

(now, the thing you need to know is that all monasteries in tibet have packs of semi-feral dogs half-guarding the place. i'm not sure exactly if they're pets, or attack dogs, or what, but they belong to the monks and are probably somehow blessed.)

anyways, this dog is barking at me. and he is pissed. this little buddy is not going to let me anywhere near the monastery, let alone back to my jeep on the other side of the buildings. at first he wasn't quite sure what to do, but he started sizing me up. circling. creeping closer. getting louder. figuring out if i might be a good substitute for dinner. then... my cell phone rang.

"hello, tim! this is your tour guide, tili!" (tili was born in india. he has a very strong accent.)

"yes tili, what's up?"

"i am down in the barking log!" (he is attempting to pronounce parking lot. roll with it.)

"that's excellent tili, i'll be down there in a few minutes."

(the dog is getting closer.)

"no no no! i said, i am down in the parking lod. you will come meet us, yes?"

"yes tili, i'll be down there in a bit."

(the dog is sweeping closer and closer. his angry bristles just brushed my pants leg.)

"ok ok. can you find your way back?"

"sure, it won't be that hard."

"ok, i will hang up now. do you need anything else?"

(at this point, i realize that tili can probably see me trying to dodge this attack animal on the mountain top. being a wise soul, i ask the local for directions.)

"tili, what do i do about the dog?"

"hit it in the head with a rock!"

"ok!"

i hang up, pick up the biggest rock near my feet, look into the dog's eyes, and say, "dog, i am going to fuck you up."

he backed away.

this being human is a guest house.
every morning a new arrival.

a joy, a depression, a meanness,
some momentary awareness comes
as an unexpected visitor.

welcome and entertain them all!
even if they're a crowd of sorrows,
who violently sweep your house
empty of its furniture,
still, treat each guest honorably.
he may be clearing you out
for some new delight.

the dark thought, the shame, the malice,
meet them at the door laughing,
and invite them in.

be grateful for whoever comes,
because each has been sent
as a guide from beyond.

~rumi

"tell me about you," he said.
"what would you like to know?" she asked.
"everything," he said.
"that could take some time," she said.
"i have time," he said.

he listened, and watched.
he looked & listened for a live mind, live heart and live eyes.

he hoped he would find contradictions.
confidence and vulnerability.
energy and stillness.
gracefulness and stumbling.
at home in a five-star hotel or eating pizza at home.
enjoying silly jokes and impassioned debate.
a personality to express and a desire to please.

he was not without checkboxes to be filled, of course;
we are none of us blank sheets.
but he did not seek perfection.
he sought someone very real.

a woman with thoughts, feelings, passions.
a woman who has known highs and lows, and been lost to neither.
a woman who has things she will not compromise.
a woman who has things about which she cares deeply.
a woman who lives a philosophy of her own creation.
a woman who rejects mediocrity.

a woman who wishes to be tied and dominated in the bedroom,
and to have doors held open for her outside it.

he knew what he sought was rare.
he knew the hunt would take time.
but he had found it before, and would find it again.
and he was in no hurry.

his friendship was widely available,
though his truly close friends few in number.
his sexuality to the compatible ones.
the whole of him, though ... everything;
that would be available only to one.
to an incredibly rare & valuable creature.

with her, he would share it all.
they would venture into dark, hard places together.
then emerge into light, laughter-filled ones.
they would share their minds, bodies, hearts, souls.
they would share their dreams and their fears.
she would share the whole of her with him, and he with her.

it would begin with the smallest step.
she would read this, and respond.
perhaps with a few paragraphs, perhaps with a few pages.

he waited, patiently.

i like the following poem, because i like dorothy parker, and it ends with a neat piece of irony.

lullaby

sleep, pretty lady, the night is enfolding you;
drift, and so lightly, on crystalline streams.
wrapped in its perfumes, the darkness is holding you;
starlight bespangles the way of your dreams.
chorus the nightingales, wistfully amorous;
blessedly quiet, the blare of the day.
all the sweet hours may your visions be glamorous-
sleep, pretty lady, as long as you may.

sleep, pretty lady, the night shall be still for you;
silvered and silent, it watches you rest.
each little breeze, in its eagerness, will for you
murmur the melodies ancient and blest.
so in the midnight does happiness capture us;
morning is dim with another day's tears.
give yourself sweetly to images rapturous-
sleep, pretty lady, a couple of years.

sleep, pretty lady, the world awaits day with you;
girlish and golden, the slender young moon.
grant the fond darkness its mystical way with you;
morning returns to us ever too soon.
roses unfold, in their loveliness, all for you;
blossom the lilies for hope of your glance.
when you're awake, all the men go and fall for you-
sleep, pretty lady, and give me a chance.

i'm willing to admit that it's hard for me to trust. i've had at least one major instance in which a deep trust was broken, and even forgoing that example, i've had a hard time really getting comfortable and trusting people with more important things. it's not that i don't trust, but it just takes me a while to determine if someone's trustworthy and i've found that many people assume that they have my trust right off the bat. i try to give people more of a chance upon first meeting them, but when things start to look serious (either in a friendship or a relationship), trust becomes something that needs to be focused on and it just comes a little more slowly than i wish it did.

also--a promise means more to me than most people think. it's the ultimate test of trust for me. once you understand me a bit and really get why it's so important, if you say that you promise something, i will put my entire trust in you following through with your promise. if you break it, it breaks my trust, and that's not something i take lightly or forgive easily.

two days came and went. they went fast like a speeding car, or maybe like an airplane. you could see the whole goddamn city from that little window. we were rising above the clouds. and then the sun was rising too and everything was all pink and yellow: the crumpled newspaper that had too many readers, the man's face who was a stranger to me and to so many others everywhere. i was reading a book, a book about a red wheelbarrow and a speeding car and a yellow dog. i was thinking about you, you and me, really. two peas in a pod came and went. that's how the story was going to begin. we landed. it was a cold and foggy day. no. it was a cold fog-bank driven day with speeding cars and too much wind. i wanted to be there: in that red wheelbarrow, because so much depended upon it, because you and me and that yellow dog could go wheelbarrowing down the whole grassy backyard with the wind in our hair, and it would feel like we were in a speeding car, only much better.

(i just read this piece at a poetry reading in san francisco with jack hirschman, sf poet laureate. i can die happy now.)

i'd rather create my own sections, which will tell you more important things.

your profile content that increases the likelihood that i will message you:

my details: religion: any of the non-theistic options or other, if you mean secular humanism. smoking: no. drinking: rarely or not at all. offspring: doesn't have kids but might want them or doesn't have kids but wants them. if you want to raise children, your reasons have more to do with children than with yourself, and you have reasons rather than unreasoned instinct or tradition.

about: you love the outdoors. you are intellectual and idealistic, and you act to make your ideals manifest. you want to have a positive effect on the people around you. you care deeply about verbal, musical, or visual artistry.

your profile content that decreases the likelihood that i will message you:

my details: religion: any of the theistic options. smoking: yes. drinking: very often, often, socially. offspring: you've left this section blank without explanation, or i can tell from other parts of your profile that you're a traditional person who lacks reasons for your hopes and goals.

about: you love bar hopping and clubbing. i am attracted to social competence, not to someone who needs to drug himself to feel interesting and interested, receptive, relaxed, outgoing, creative, and open-minded. you say that you're sarcastic. i am not attracted to a derisive or passive-aggressive talk style. you're addicted to video games. i enjoy playing them with clients to teach them pragmatics, but i do not date or form friendships with people who prefer to spend more time with video games than with people. you say that you're "simple." there's a difference between appreciating simplicity and being simple. appreciating nature is different from being simple. explaining complex concepts or performing complex tasks so well that they seem simple is different from being simple. even when you were a single cell, you were complex.

some clarification about the "i'm looking for" section:

i am looking for long-term dating, and at first, i also checked short-term dating as an indication of attitude more than a goal. i can value a relationship or experience regardless of how long it lasted if i enjoyed it and learned from it. just because an experience has a short duration doesn't mean it wasn't real or important. however, "looking for" implies an intended outcome, which is distinct from an attitude about an unintended outcome.

i'm looking for a long-term date who by definition is also a friend. i am open to male or female friends as a separate category from dates, and i have made some friends from a dating site whom i never dated, when it's clear that we're not compatible for dating (it helps if one is gay and the other is not, but that's not the only way to clarity). however, i am not looking for the passive, shy type of person who wants to be "friends first," all the while hoping to date me and wondering why he often remains in the friend role. i am looking for the infinitesimal number of people who correctly understand that "looking for" means looking for, and not "telling myself i'm ok with." i'm looking for people who know what they want in a date and what they want in a friend and who know the difference between them.

whether those reasons are shallow or justified, i countdown the top 11 professionals one would be wise to steer clear of.

11. sheepskin benchmonkeys
sheepskin benchmonkeys, a.k.a. those type of all or nothing academic indentured servants who owe the professor all their time and they still believe that a phd is going to be their guarantee somehow worth all the lack of real world success and lifestyle including dating satisfaction that they've been postponing for years.

10. air hosts/hostesses
air hosts, a.k.a flight attendants, b.k.a international players: traveling the world gives you a lot of room to hide your dirty laundry and a lot time to do it.

9. police officers
police officers are ordered to serve and protect, which, loosely translated for those that choose to date them, means long work hours and lots of danger. if you lack understanding, patience or faith, you can never date a cop.

8. personal trainers
all day, your super-fit girlfriend/boyfriend is being admired by men and women. trainers are motivators/teachers, and remember back in the day when you fell in love with your teacher? now imagine that teacher pushing your leg back for stretches while you're hot and sweaty. sounds like a bad porno already.

7. writers/bloggers
your whole relationship can be an ongoing interview, and every incident is a potential story idea. a writer's life is made up of constant deadlines, which may interfere with the amount of attention he or she is able to give you.

6. models
we're not talking about the kind who book church fashion shows... they're safe. however, if you are dating a person who makes the runway and photo shoots their career, you have to be insanely secure and confident. anything less will make you miss out on the bliss of dating a model in the first place.

5. bartenders
bartenders make money off their looks, and they love attention. mixologists have mastered the game of flirting and teasing, conditioning them to be very insincere with their feelings even when they don't intend to be.

4. psychiatrist/psychologists/counselors
it's like dating a writer, but 100 times worse. you are analyzed, studied, examined and evaluated by someone who has been taught the human psyche. in the middle of argument, you can never say, "you don't know what you're talking about!"

3. professional athletes
three words: away games. groupies.

2. strippers
just because t-pain fell in love with his local pole dancer and made a song about it, doesn't mean you have to. dating either a male or female stripper means breaking through and ignoring all the stereotypes associated with it. you must be able to handle your partner being adored for his/her sexuality, and them loving money maybe more than they love you.

1. unemployed
this doesn't refer to those who have been laid off in rough economic times, but those who make unemployment a full-time job, figuring out how they can go through life without ever having to find work. without much to occupy their time, they will become an annoyance when all their focus is put on you, but the lack of individual ambition is also a telltale sign of someone who won't be participating in the growth of the relationship.

someone once asked me for a list of 25 things about myself that not everyone knew. maybe this is an appropriate place to include it... numbered zero to 24, of course.

0 - i didn't write this in facebook, i wrote it in eudora. thank you and good evening.

1 - i was aboard a virgin 747 on climbout from sfo when a bird strike took out one of its engines.

2 - if i'd got up at the right time that day, i would have been at the wrong place at the wrong time for the manchester ira bomb.

3 - i'm partially left handed and partially right handed.

4 - i get migraines if my blood sugar gets too low, hence i can't fast.

5 - i had a benign lump removed from my head when i was about 28.

6 - i've never broken a bone or had stitches.

7 - i like things which hypnotise me - machines, music, speed (motion, that is, not the drug, which i haven't tried), presentations (sometimes), going to the optician (weirdly), etc...

8 - i generally approach situations with an attitude which approximates to "what would make the machine work best?", regardless of what i'm actually dealing with.

9 - i don't trust anything unless i know how it works, down to the wire.

10 - i like things that have purity of vision in their concept - examples would be macintosh, rx-7, motm, klein, belgian beer, etc.

11 - i was allergic to duck for several years. well, i don't know whether it was actually an allergy, but it acted like one. i couldn't even smell it without gagging. almost like the allergy i had to vodka for seven years following a particularly protracted experience, but different, honest.

12 - i couldn't belch until i was 33 years old. turns out it's a genetic thing, my cousin was similarly affected.

13 - i am a stickler for correct spelling and punctuation. america's idiocratic culture is invading the world, backed up by the military, and that's devolution and degeneration, not evolution. we should be celebrating our languages' idiosyncratic features, not mangling them. they will never take me alive.

14 - i don't have heroes really but the closest i do have is probably michael palin. he's normal, and a genius as well. and he didn't call me when he came to rockridge, which nearly cost him his almost-hero status.

15 - i spent most of the time i lived in rossendale, lancashire wishing that food came in little pills rather than shapeless colourless blobs. since leaving rossendale, i've grown to love food and have become a half decent cook. and of course the irony of all this is that i can't take pills.

16 - i regard most drugs as just excuses for not dealing with one's life. of course, this does not include anything i personally like, such as alcohol in most forms and occasional dabbling in marijuana.

17 - i had classical flute training from when i was 10 or so till - beh, i don't remember - 14 maybe. i could play reasonably well and was a member of various school bands and such. my lessons all ended one day when the teacher made a mistake by thinking that we had stopped going, when in fact we were just on holiday, and booked someone else in our slot. my mother threw a tantrum and that was that.

18 - before i knew better, i was largely conservative. i thought that people could make their lives whatever they wanted them to be, regardless of their background. now i believe that our society's most important function is to ensure that our children get the education they deserve. blaming kids for being born into poor families is simply selling our world's future to useless rich people for a few lousy bucks.

19 - imho, religion and intelligence are mutually exclusive.

20 - i've never really had "normal" jobs, as people might describe them. i've never worked as a waiter or in any retail capacity. the closest job i had to anything like that was working in a print finishing company, handling machines which made books and magazines out of printed sheets. i got my first engineering job when i was 20.

21 - during the time i was supposed to be paying attention at school, i scribbled instead. i wrote a fantasy novel when i was 15, and countless short stories etc. i even wrote crappy uninformed porn, which my mother found while clearing out my room. i couldn't stop myself writing.

22 - i joined the lovemakers in 2002, signed a major label deal in 2004, and quit in 2006.

23 - i did aids/lifecycle 7, and i'm signing up for next year. people ask me why we do such a crazy thing, and offer various "is it this?" answers. i usually answer "all of the above", but the main reasons are (1) there is hiv in the family, and (2) it's such a ridiculous thing to do that it has to be done.

24 - i'm not really a proctor. i'm more of a smithies.

25 - i think anything is worth doing if it's funny

26 - i think life's funnier if you're crap

27 - i spent my 18th birthday at a mediaeval castle in cheshire

i have attempted to abstain from frequenting this digital parlour
in the past, but i inevitably find myself wandering its many
disappointing corridors of broken hearts, and forlorn glances, if
only to deepen the wounds upon my heart from when i last came to
the okcupid.

'tis a tragic story, if you wish to humor this lady's tale.

it began in the summer of 1894, where edward norton still ruled san
francisco and tea time was not disrespected as it is today. in
fact, twas the best year for tea times, before sir rutherman iii
took that nasty fall involving the tribals and the oriental ghost
upon the bungalow in paris in the february of '95 and sir gahveryly
took over and popularized all those ghastly reforms. but i digress.
i was dallying the pages of the okcupid, admiring the sights (as
much as a fine lady can admire the mish mash of cads, hooligans,
and boorish louts), when a gentleman called upon my doorstep,
leaving a telegram of awkward proposals and a date upon a zeppelin.
although awkward and fumbling i was none too offended by his
demeanor, nor did he completely lack of charm, so we arranged to
meet by zeppelin on the saturday of the week.

we met upon the zeppelin, admired the peaks and valleys of san
francisco, drank tea, and discussed the current policies put forth
by edward norton recently concerning kittens and galvanic
equipment. things were rather tepid for the most part, my gentleman
companion, some paul v brown or somesuch, until a vicious sky
pirate came upon us! using his air dirigible, his motley crew
raided our luxury craft and went about looting and stealing all
they could get their grubby hands on.

oh! but the captain! that captain of the ship! how dashing he was!
unlike the filthy curs going every which way laying their grubby
hands on any treasure, he stood above them like some beautiful
marble david, as if the world were some mighty goliath he just
slain. whether it be confidence or arrogance smitten across his
face, i knew that his soul was forever smitten upon my heart. some
such reason could be why my mouth spoke these words before i could
even stop myself:

"oh pirate! you can plunder the gold, steal the treasures, ransack
the reserves! but i will not be satisfied unless you whisk me away
upon your mighty vessel!"

i instantly covered my mouth and moved back to hide. but 'twas too
late; his gaze met mine, and he slowly walked, with swagger and
glamour towards me. i could do nothing, i was paralyzed, my heart
was pounding out of passion or fear i knew not but my gentleman was
absolutely terrified. "back, scoundrel!" he shouted as he drew his
rapier, but the pirate king merely slapped it aside with nary a
thought then lay a good left hook across his face. while impressed
by my friend's momentary courage, i swooned at the pirate;s
virility. soon i was in his arms and whisked back upon his
airship.

i joined the pirate king on his many voyages across the sky for
several months as a impassioned companion and partner in crime. we
raided, we loved, we sang and drank and ate, and he made sure not
another pirate layed even a finger upon me. while surrounded by
dogs, he was more of a gentleman than any mainland ponce. something
though always pried in the back of my mind, a worm of doubt that
wriggled through the apple of my paradise. for you see, at least
once a day my pirate king would disappear for perhaps an hour or
two on end every day, unable to be found anywhere i could get to
upon the ship.

one day, when we were to have tea upon the poop deck of the ship,
he was absent. i inquired around the ship for his presence but none
knew where he was. so i pilfered the desk at our quarters (being
now a pirate queen i have learned a little of loose moralities),
and found upon a hidden drawer a key to the hold that i've never
seen before. there was one chamber in the hold that was perpetually
locked; while perplexing i knew not to push my curiosities too far.
but however, on this day, my instincts told me that i must discover
what was behind that door. so down i went, putting key to lock, and
discovering what lay behind the forbidden door...

oh the shock! the horror! there was paul v green or somesuch there
clad in the most revealing and unusual of black leather garment,
and my dear pirate king bent over like some serf licking his boots!
i almost didn't recognize my dear as he had on some horrendous
leather mask but i could tell from the depths of the eyes behind it
that it was indeed my love, my companion scoundrel ruler. for i was
not the only one stolen from the zeppelin on that fateful day, but
so was my gentleman caller! and there he was, partaking in some
horrid ritual of servitude and utter debauchery! i left, tears
streaming down my eyes and a virulent mixture of rage and bitter
betrayal brewing a toxic concoction upon my soul.

i stole a life ship and as much loot as i could sneak off that
night. i made a new name and a new life. i returned to the annals
of the okcupid. but lo and behold, on my return to society, i
discovered the profile of the very same pirate king upon my
okcupid, who in fact showed up as a "similar user" to the paul
whatshisname! similar except he was marked as "more kinky", and
marked as "bi" and "available"! oh, the shame i felt! to be turned
aside in favor of a kink-gaylord-fancy-nancy! my heart has been
irreparable to this day, which is why i have cast off from the
harbor of okcupid to set sail and swear off the lands of love and
caring forever.

for most of my life i had an irrational yet debilitating fear of space aliens. there is an orange tree outside the window of my bedroom in the house where i grew up; for many years, generations of small nocturnal rodents have been enjoying the tree and its fruits, but i was always afraid to look because they might be space aliens.

this fear did not truly go away until my fourth year of college, when i took a semester of astronomy. for anyone who hasn't taken any astronomy or watched the discovery channel, i will summarize the concept of space with some brief, sweeping generalizations: space is huge; everything is very far apart, and although we have developed fancy technology to see things far away in the huge emptiness of space, in general what we have seen thus far are really big balls of gas.

i was also semi-permanently traumatized by "the exorcist". when i was young my mind would bring up a frightening image, and there was no way to purge it except turning on the lights. subsequently my nightmares involved finding myself in a dark room and not being able to turn on the lights.

well, i'm going to do something here and be completely honest about something i've never been completely honest about before. i'm sure that it's a terrible idea, and that in the end i'm going to regret it, but here goes anyways.

ever since i was little, i've always been interested in crossdressing.

okay, yes, i know, weird. it really doesn't mesh with any other aspect of my personality. if anyone who knows me ever happens to read this, i'm sure i'll never hear the end of it.

but it won't go away. for years (literally) i've done my best to just kind of ignore it, hoping it would just up and leave me alone. i've had little outbursts where i could sort of express it in limited doses, and after these doses all urges would disappear for about a week, before coming back full force later on. so since ignoring it has done absolutely nothing but make it worse, i'm trying out a new strategy. einstein once said that the definition of insanity is doing the same thing over and over while expecting different results. well, i figure i'm insane enough at this point so i might as well go in the opposite direction.

so here i am. i guess i should sort of clarify a bit. i don't want to be a girl, i'm just a boy who likes girls clothes. i'm not particularly feminine, and i'm not flamboyant in the least, so it's hard to justify to people that know me.

also, it's hard to justify to myself considering my own personality. i'm a fighter at heart. i love conflict, and i love pitting myself against other people be it in actual physical contests, or in debates or other such arenas. these urges go against pretty much everything i am, or so i tell myself.

despite all this, i might as well try it and see what happens. i would like to meet people who either are interested in the same, or who just like people like me. my ideal boyfriend would probably like me doing it, who might even push me to do it, but isn't interested in doing it himself. i'm completely new to it. i've never dressed up and gone out in any seriousness, i don't have any clothes, and i don't really know where to start.

the reason i'm even putting this on here is that i don't think it's very fair of me to not have any mention of it on such a personal website as this where i may possibly meet a guy that i could end up dating. and who knows, maybe someone is out there just as crazy as me, and actually likes it or finds it attractive. i figure, it's san francisco, i'm sure there are all types here.

i'm a top. ok ok, how about 25 random things i'm not too embarrassed to admit:

1. i've hung out on separate occasions with two different members of the village people. several years ago i had the pleasure of spending the afternoon with filipe rose (the indian) during san francisco's pride celebration. years later, after attending a 'very merry disco christmas' at the castro theater, i got the opportunity to hang out with randy jones (the cowboy) who was both incredibly sweet and very personable. to this day "can't stop the music" remains one of my favorite movies of all time. i feel fortunate i was able to see the original village people perform in concert in vancouver many moons ago.

2. i played baby garfield in an elementary school musical production. i even had a solo singing part! i don't remember much about the experience except i rather over-acted through the whole thing. it would be the end of my acting career.

3. i love horror movies! i can watch the most gory, stomach-turning films without having nightmares and yet i have arachnophobia. if you want to see me lose it, watch arachnophobia with me one night and watch me freak out. i can't stand spiders.

4. i am a total kid at heart. i can spend hours in novelty gift and toy stores. i still love to go to amusement parks and ride roller coasters.

5. i dream of one day owning a modern home like something out of the pages of dwell. the design within reach catalog is my idea of porn.

6. when i was a child my brother and sisters told me i was adopted and made me cry.

7. my feelings are hurt easily.

8. i am addicted to reality tv. i can't get enough of it. i love it all--project runway, real housewives, america's next top model, top chef, american idol, celebrity apprentice, wife swap, survivor--you name it. if it's reality tv, chances are i've got a season pass on my tivo.

9. i love the 80s!--the music, the movies, the fashion. i still love watching reruns of degrassi junior high and get excited watching a good john hughes film. sixteen candles, the breakfast club, and pretty in pink are my coming-of-age movies. i'm thrilled to have had the opportunity to see some of my favorite artists in concert over the past few years: human league, duran duran, abc, howard jones, dead or alive, berlin, pet shop boys, erasure.

10. i used to go out dancing in the most embarrassing outfits when i was younger. the pice de rsistance was going out clubbing in a jockstrap with a pair of bare-assed chaps in the middle of a snowstorm. to this day, i wonder what on earth i was thinking.

11. i don't want to grow up.

12. i still get excited when i find out bananarama are releasing a new single.

13. my mother once made me order her the flowbee, an electric powered vacuum attachment made for cutting hair. to my horror i actually ordered it, but fortunately it never arrived.

14. i was upset when wham split up.

15. when i was 19, i drank an entire bottle of red wine before a night out dancing. before i could make it to the club i proceeded to throw up in my best friend's car. i am thankful she forgave me. and to my brother who had to clean up the mess. those white denim jeans would never be the same.

16. i still enjoy watching cartoons. i believe that sid & marty krofft and pee wee herman are underrated geniuses.

17. i get lost easily. it's painfully embarrassing. i have no sense of direction and am usually clueless to my whereabouts. i read maps upside-down.

18. i have no idea what i am doing with my life and that terrifies me.

19. i have a brother a year older than myself, who many people mistake for my twin. we look alike, sound alike, and act alike. we are so similar but completely different.

20. i once went to a triple feature of rollerboogie, xanadu, and skatetown usa. it was one of the best nights of my life.

21. i do not cook. everything i eat is either frozen, boiled, canned, or takeout. tragic.

22. i miss living in vancouver all the time. not a day goes by that i don't think about what it'd be like if i moved back.

23. i am secretly envious of happy couples.

24. i am afraid of dying alone.

a man and an ostrich walk into a restaurant. the waitress asks, "what will it be?"
the man replied "a burger and a coke." "and you?" "i'll have the same," the ostrich replies. they finish their meal and pay. "that will be $4.50," the man reached into his pocket and pulled out the exact amount. they do this every day till fri.
"the usual?" she asked. "no, today is friday. i'll have steak and a coke."
"me too." says the ostrich. they finish and pay. "that will be $10.95"
the man reached in and pulls out the exact amount again just like all week.
the waitress was dumb-founded. "how is it that you always have the exact amount?"
"well," says the man. "i was cleaning my attic and i found a dusty lamp. i rubbed it and a genie appeared." wow!" said the waitress. "what did you wish for?"
"i asked that when i needed to pay for something, the exact amount would appear in my pocket." "amazing! most people would ask for a million dollars. but what's with the ostrich?" "well," said the man. "i also asked for a chick with long legs."
